</div><p></p><p> Former Home Office minister Ms Mactaggart said his position had become “unsustainable” while fellow ex-minister Mr Spellar said Mr Corbyn’s behaviour over the Syria vote had been “unacceptable”. </p><p> <iframe frameborder="0" height="350" id="tweetframe" scrolling="no" src="http://renderer.qmerce.com/interaction/565832cf42f2dd112b4357ee" width="100%"></iframe></p><p> Jeremy Corbyn took the unprecedented step on Friday night of emailing Labour supporters to seek their views on whether Parliament should vote to authorise airstrikes in Syria. </p><p> <span class="ssImg "><img alt="Corbyn letter to Labour members" height="549" src="http://i.telegraph.co.uk/multimedia/archive/03512/labour-letter_3512578a.JPG" version="b" width="448"/><span class="artImageExtras" style="max-width:448px;"><span class="ingCaptionCredit"><span class="caption">Corbyn letter to Labour members</span><span class="credit">  Photo: Labour party</span></span></span></span></p><p> "I am writing to consult you on what you think Britain should do. Should Parliament vote to authorise the bombing of Syria?" Mr Corbyn wrote in the 224 word missive to members. </p><p> Meanwhile a third ex-Labour minister minister Frank Field came forward to insist that the party "needs an alternative leader". </p><p> The Birkenhead MP told Iain Dale on LBC that the current turmoil in the party will go on "until there's a credible leader as an alternative and that is nowhere in sight". </p><p> He said: "There'll be no challenge to Jeremy until we have somebody emerge who's got the stature, who looks like a leader of the Labour Party, more importantly a Prime Minister in waiting." </p><p> <iframe allowtransparency="allowtransparency" frameborder="0" height="300" id="player1" scrolling="no" src="//embeds.audioboom.com/boos/3860668-frank-field-labour-needs-an-alternative-leader/embed/v4?eid=AQAAAHv8V1a86DoA" style="background-color:transparent; display:block; max-width: 700px;" title="audioBoom player" width="100%"></iframe></p><p> The news came as Mr Corbyn cancelled a day’s campaigning in Oldham ahead of Thursday’s by-election to deal with <a href="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/syria/12019854/Jeremy-Corbyn-facing-resignations-as-shadow-cabinet-back-David-Cameron-air-strikes.html">the escalating crisis engulfing his leadership of the Labour Party</a>. </p><p> The Labour leader was due to spend only his second day campaigning today ahead of next week’s Oldham West and Royton by-election, the first electoral test of his leadership. </p><p>
