</div><p></p><p> However Mr Corbyn cancelled the campaigning to hold meetings in London amid <a href="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/syria/12019854/Jeremy-Corbyn-facing-resignations-as-shadow-cabinet-back-David-Cameron-air-strikes.html">widespread reports that more than half of the MPs in his shadow cabinet might resign</a> if they are told to vote against David Cameron’s plans to send in British jets to bomb Isil in Syria. </p><p> Mr Corbyn is now fighting to hold his party together. This morning Hillary Benn, the shadow Foreign Secretary, was forced to say on national radio that he was not quitting over Syria. </p><p> David Cameron, the Prime Minister, said that Labour MPs should "do the right thing" and back the Government's "compelling case" for British military action against so-called Islamic State in Syria. </p><p> Mr Corbyn has <a href="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/Jeremy_Corbyn/12014388/Wheres-Jeremy-Corbyn-Labour-leader-hardly-seen-in-Oldham-West-and-Royton-by-election.html">only campaigned once – on November 6</a> – in the safe Labour constituency - which was held by veteran MP Michael Meacher for decades - where the party is in a straight fight with the UK Independence Party. </p><p> His face rarely appears on local by election leaflets amid concerns that his positions on security issues are turning off voters. </p><p> <span class="ssImg "><img alt="Jeremy Corbyn features on just one Labour leaflet in the Oldham West and Royton by-election" height="427" src="http://i.telegraph.co.uk/multimedia/archive/03508/oldham-leaflet-cor_3508873b.jpg" version="b" width="620"/><span class="artImageExtras" style="max-width:620px;"><span class="ingCaptionCredit"><span class="caption">JEREMY CORBYN FOUND! He appears on just one Labour leaflet in the Oldham West and Royton by-election</span></span></span></span></p><p> Mr Corbyn is fighting to hold his party together amid <a href="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/syria/12019854/Jeremy-Corbyn-facing-resignations-as-shadow-cabinet-back-David-Cameron-air-strikes.html">widespread reports that more than half of the MPs in his shadow cabinet might resign</a> if they are told to vote against David Cameron’s plans to send in British jets to bomb Isil in Syria. </p><p> He is now facing the biggest week of his leadership, with crunch meetings of his shadow Cabinet and wider Parliamentary Labour Party on Monday, and the by-election on Thursday. </p><p> Ministers accused Mr Corbyn of being “fundamentally dishonest” and treating them with “contempt” after he wrote to MPs saying he cannot support air strikes. </p><p> <iframe frameborder="0" height="350" id="tweetframe" scrolling="no" src="http://renderer.qmerce.com/interaction/5638971941d4754d14ee4a97" width="100%"></iframe></p><p> That came hours after he had told a shadow Cabinet meeting that they would reach a “collective decision” at another shadow Cabinet meeting on Monday. </p><p> Emily Thornberry, a shadow Employment minister who backed Mr Corbyn to be leader, urged him to diffuse the crisis by allowing MPs a free vote on Syria. </p><p> She told BBC Radio 4's Today's programme: "We do usually act collectively but I think on issues like this there are times when people cannot stick to a whip that is imposed." </p><p> <style type="text/css">.tg-pullquote__global__group{zoom: 1;}.tg-pullquote__global__group:before, .tg-pullquote__global__group:after{content: ""; display: table;}.tg-pullquote__global__group:after{clear: both;}.tg-pullquote__inline{float:left;}.tg-pullquote__content{margin: 0 20px 10px 0px; font-size:18px; line-height:23px; font-family:georgia; width:260px; float:left;}.tg-pullquote__content--mobile{float: none; font-size: 18px; margin-left: 4.687%; margin-right: 4.687%; width: 90.626%;}.tg-pullquote__title{font-family:arial; font-weight:bold; font-size:16px; border-top:1px dotted #000000;}.tg-pullquote__quote{color:#007A8F; font-style:italic; margin-top:5px; margin-bottom: